help.alternate: Whether or not the injectors should be fired at the same time. This setting is ignored when Sequential is selected below, however it will still affect the req_fuel value.
help.engineType: Engines with an equal number of degrees between all firings (This is most engines) should select Even fire. Some 2 and 6 cylinder engines are Odd fire however.
help.mapSample: The method used for calculating the MAP reading\nFor 1-2 Cylinder engines, Cycle Minimum is recommended.\nFor more than 2 cylinders Cycle Average is recommended
help.stoich: The stoichiometric ration of the fuel being used. For flex fuel, choose the primary fuel
help.injLayout:
The injector layout and timing to be used. Options are: 
 1. Paired - 2 injectors per output. Outputs active is equal to half the number of cylinders. Outputs are timed over 1 crank revolution. 
 2. Semi-sequential: Same as paired except that injector channels are mirrored (1&4, 2&3) meaning the number of outputs used are equal to the number of cylinders. Only valid for 4 cylinders or less. 
 3. Banked: 2 outputs only used. 
 4. Sequential: 1 injector per output and outputs used equals the number of cylinders. Injection is timed over full cycle.
help.TrigPattern: The type of input trigger decoder to be used.
help.useResync: If enabled, sync will be rechecked once every full cycle from the cam input. This is good for accuracy, however if your cam input is noisy then this can cause issues.
help.trigPatternSec: Cam mode/type also known as Secondary Trigger Pattern.
help.numTeeth: Number of teeth on Primary Wheel.
help.missingTeeth: Number of Missing teeth on Primary Wheel.
help.TrigAng: The Angle ATDC when tooth No:1 on the primary wheel passes the primary sensor. The range of this field is -360 to +360 degrees.
help.TrigAngMul: A multiplier used by non-360 degree tooth wheels (i.e. Wheels where the tooth count doesn't divide evenly into 360. Usage: (360 * <multiplier>) / tooth_count = Whole number
help.SkipCycles: The number of revolutions that will be skipped during cranking before the injectors and coils are fired.
help.TrigEdge: The Trigger edge of the primary sensor.\nLeading.\nTrailing.
help.TrigEdgeSec: The Trigger edge of the secondary (Cam) sensor.\nLeading.\nTrailing.
help.TrigFilter: Tuning of the trigger filter algorithm. The more aggressive the setting, the more noise will be removed, however this increases the chance of some true readings being filtered out (False positive). Medium is safe for most setups. Only select 'Aggressive' if no other options are working
help.sparkMode: Wasted Spark: Ignition outputs are on the channels <= half the number of cylinders. Eg 4 cylinder outputs on IGN1 and IGN2.\nSingle Channel: All ignition pulses are output on IGN1.\nWasted COP: Ignition pulses are output on all ignition channels up to the number of cylinders. Eg 4 cylinder outputs on all ignition channels. Note that your board needs to have same number of igntion outputs as cylinders to be able to run this
help.IgInv: Whether the spark fires when the ignition signal goes high or goes low. Nearly all ignition systems use 'Going Low' but please verify this as damage to coils can result from the incorrect selection. (NOTE: THIS IS NOT MEGASQUIRT. THIS SETTING IS USUALLY THE OPPOSITE OF WHAT THEY USE!)
help.sparkDur: The duration of the spark at full dwell. Typically around 1ms
help.fixAngEnable: If enabled, timing will be locked/fixed and the ignition map will be ignored. Note that this value will be overriden by the fixed cranking value when cranking
help.FixAng: Timing will be locked at this value if the above is enabled
help.crankRPM: The cranking RPM threshold. When RPM is lower than this value (and above 0) the system will be considered to be cranking
help.tpsflood: Keep throttle over this value to disable the priming pulse and cranking fuel. Used to prevent flood or clear already flooded engine
help.fanHyster: The number of degrees of hysteresis to be used in controlling the fan. Recommended values are between 2 and 5
help.fanWhenCranking: Whether the fan should be disabled or continue running when the engine is cranking
help.fanWhenOff: Whether the fan will continue to run when the engine is turned off
help.fanPin: The Arduino pin that the fan control signal will output on. This is NOT necesarrily the same as the connector pin on any particlar board
help.fanSP: The trigger temperature for the fan. Fan will be enabled above this temp
help.vssPulsesPerKm: The number of pulses on the VSS signal per KM/Mile
help.vssSmoothing: A smoothing factor to help reduce noise in the VSS signal. Typical values are between 0 and 50
help.aeTime: The duration of the acceleration enrichment
help.iacChannels: The number of output channels used for PWM valves. Select 1 for 2-wire valves or 2 for 3-wire valves.
help.iacStepTime: Duration of each stepping pulse. Values that are too low can cause the motor to behave erratically or not at all. See the manual for suggested step times
help.iacCoolTime: Cool time between each step. Set to zero if you don't want any cooling at all
help.iacStepHome: Homing steps to perform on startup. Must be greater than the fully open steps value
help.iacMaxSteps: Maximum number of steps the IAC can be moved away from the home position. Should always be less than Homing steps.
help.iacStepHyster: The minimum number of steps to move in any one go.
help.iacAlgorithm:
Selects method of idle control.
None = no idle control valve.
On/Off valve.
PWM valve (2,3 wire).
Stepper Valve (4,6,8 wire).
help.iacPWMdir: Normal PWM valves increase RPM with higher duty. If RPM decreases with higher duty then select Reverse
help.iacCLminDuty: When using closed loop idle control, this is the minimum duty cycle that the PID loop will allow. Combined with the maximum value, this specifies the working range of your idle valve
help.iacCLmaxDuty: When using closed loop idle control, this is the maximum duty cycle that the PID loop will allow. Combined with the minimum value, this specifies the working range of your idle valve
help.iacTPSlimit: When using OL+CL idle control, if the TPS is higher than this value closed loop idle resets the integeral of the PID (To prevent RPM dips comming back to idle)
help.iacRPMlimitHysteresis: When using closed loop idle control, if the closed loop Target RPM + this value is higher than the actual RPM, closed loop idle resets the integeral of the PID (To prevent RPM dips comming back to idle)
help.iacFastTemp: Below this temperature, the idle output will be high (On). Above this temperature, it will turn off.
help.idleUpPolarity: Normal polarity is a ground switch where an earthed signal activates the Idle Up. The internal pullup will be enabled with Normal polarity. \n Inverted may be used if a 5v signal is used to enable the Idle Up.
help.CTPSPolarity: Normal polarity is a ground switch where an earthed signal activates the closed throttle position. The internal pullup will be enabled with Normal polarity. \n Inverted may be used if a 5v signal is used to enable the closed throttle position.
help.idleUpAdder: The amount (In either Duty Cycle % or Steps (Depending on the idle control method in use), that the idle control will increase by when Idle Up is active
help.idleAdvEnabled: Added setting adds curve values to current spark table values when user defined idle is active. \n Switched setting overrides spark table values and uses curve values for idle ignition timing.
help.idleAdvAlgorithm: Use Throttle position sensor (TPS) or closed throttle position sensor (CTPS) to detect idle state.
help.idleAdvDelay: The number of seconds after sync is achieved before the idle advance control begins
help.idleTaperTime: Soft time transition from crank to running PWM targets
help.oddfire2: The ATDC angle of channel 2 for oddfire engines. This is relative to the TDC angle of channel 1
help.oddfire3: The ATDC angle of channel 3 for oddfire engines. This is relative to the TDC angle of channel 1 (NOT channel 2)
help.oddfire4: The ATDC angle of channel 4 for oddfire engines. This is relative to the TDC angle of channel 1 (NOT channel 3)
help.aeColdPct: Acceleration enrichment adjustment for cold engine. Cold adjustment % is tapered between start and end temperatures.\n100% = no adjustment.
help.aeColdTaperMin: AE cold adjustment taper start temperature. When coolant is below this value, full cold adjustment is applied.
help.aeColdTaperMax: AE cold adjustment taper end temperature. When coolant is above this value, no cold adjustment is applied.
help.dfcoRPM: The RPM above which DFCO will be active. Typically set a few hundred RPM above maximum idle speed
help.dfcoHyster: Hysteresis for DFCO RPM. 200-300 RPM is typical for this, however a higher value may be needed if the RPM is fluctuating around the cutout speed
help.dfcoTPSThresh: The TPS value below which DFCO will be active. Typical value is 5%-10%, but higher may be needed if TPS signal is noisy
help.launchPin: The ARDUINO pin that the clutch switch is connected to. This is NOT the pin on the connector, but the pin it relates to on the arduino
help.launchHiLo: Whether the signal is High or Low when the clutch pedal is engaged. For a ground switching input (Most clutch switches), this should be LOW
help.lnchPullRes: Whether the internal pullup resistor is enabled or left floating. For a ground switching input (Most clutch switches), select Pullup. For a 0v-5v input, select Floating
help.ignBypassPin: The ARDUINO pin that the ignition bypass is connected to. This is NOT the pin on the connector, but the pin it relates to on the arduino
help.ignBypassEnable: If turned on, a ground signal will be output during cranking on the specified pin. This is used to bypass the Speeduino ignition control during cranking.
help.ignCranklock: On certain low resolution ignition patterns, the cranking timing can be locked to occur when a pulse is recieved.
help.multiplyMAP: If enabled, the MAP reading is included directly into the pulsewidth calculation by multiplying the VE lookup value by the MAP:Baro ratio. This results in a flatter VE table that can be easier to tune in some instances. VE table must be retuned when this value is changed.
help.legacyMAP: Use the legacy method of reading the MAP sensor that was used prior to the 201905 firmware. This should ONLY be enabled if you are upgrading from a firmware earlier than this
help.includeAFR: When enabled, the current AFR reading is incorporated directly in the pulsewidth calculation as a percentage of the current target ratio. VE table must be retuned when this value is changed.
help.incorporateAFR: When enabled, the AFR stoich/AFR target -ratio is incorporated directly in the pulsewidth calculation. When enabled, AFR target table affects pulsewidth even with EGO disabled. VE table must be retuned when this value is changed.
help.useExtBaro: By Default, Speeduino will measure barometric pressure upon startup. Optionally however, a 2nd pressure sensor can be used to perform live barometric readings whilst the system is on.
help.flexEnabled: Turns on readings from the Flex sensor and enables the below adjustments
help.flexFreqLow: The frequency of the sensor at 0% ethanol (50Hz for standard GM/Continental sensor)
help.flexFreqHigh: The frequency of the sensor at 100% ethanol (150Hz for standard GM/Continental sensor)
help.flexFuelAdj: Fuel % to be used for the current ethanol % (Typically 100% @ 0%, 163% @ 100%)
help.flexAdvAdj: Additional advance (in degrees) for the current ethanol % (Typically 0 @ 0%, 10-20 @ 100%)
help.flexBoostAdj: Adjustment, in kPa, to the boost target for the current ethanol %. Negative values are allowed to lower boost at lower ethanol % if necessary.
help.n2o_arming_pin: Pin that the nitrous arming/enagement switch is on.
help.n2o_pin_polarity: Whether Nitrous is active (Armed) when the pin is LOW or HIGH. If LOW is selected, the internal pullup will be used.
help.flatSArm: The RPM switch point that determines whether an eganged clutch is for launch control or flat shift. Below this figure, an engaged clutch is considered to be for launch, above this figure an active clutch input will be considered a flat shift. This should be set at least several hundred RPM above idle
help.flatSSoftWin: The number of RPM below the flat shift point where the softlimit will be applied (aka Soft limit window). Recommended values are 200-1000
help.flatSRetard: The absolute timing (BTDC) that will be used when within the soft limit window
help.engineProtectType: Whether the engine protect an rev limiter will cut the fuel, the ignition or both
help.hardCutType: How the cuts should be performed for rev/launch limits. Full cut will stop all fuel/ignition events, Rolling cut will step through all ignition outputs, only cutting a limited number per revolution
help.SoftLimitMode: Fixed: the soft limiter will retard the ignition advance to the specified value.\nRelative: current timing advance will be retarted by the specified amount
help.HardRevLim: The hard rev limit is the point that the fuel or ignition (or both) will be cut completely to reduce increasing RPMs
help.engineProtectMaxRPM: The RPM point that engine protections will engage from. Below this RPM value, engine protections will NOT be active
help.fuel2InputPin: The Arduino pin that is being used to trigger the second fuel table to be active
help.fuel2InputPolarity: Whether the 2nd fuel table should be active when input is high or low. This should be LOW for a typical ground switching input
help.fuel2InputPullup: Whether to use the built in PULLUP for the switching input. This should be Yes for a typical ground switching input
help.enable_secondarySerial: This Enables the secondary serial port . Secondary serial is serial3 on mega2560 processor, and Serial2 on STM32 and Teensy processor
help.cltAdvValues: This curve can be used to advance ignition timing when engine is warming up. This can also be used to warm up the catalytic converters in cold start by retarding timing. Or even as safety feature to retard timing when engine is too hot to prevent knock.
help.true_address: This is the 11bit Can address of the Speeduino ECU
help.realtime_base_address: This is the 11bit CAN address of the realtime data broadcast from the Speeduino ECU. This MUST be at least 0x16 greater than the true address

help.fpPrime: Duration to power fuel pump on to ensure fuel line pressure.
help.primingDelay: Delay to priming after fuel pump is on, used to wait fuel line get pressurized correctly.
help.idleUpOutputEnabled: Enable an output that is toggled by the idle up input pin. An example use is driving an AC fan relay.
help.idleUpOutputInv: No = When the idle up pin is high the output is active (grounding), when the idle up pin is low the output is inactive. Yes = When the idle up pin is high the output is inactive, when the idle up pin is low the output is active (grounding).
help.crankingEnrichTaper: Taper time from cranking enrichment to ASE or run (after engine has started).
help.lnchCtrlTPS: The minimum RPM that launch control will engage at
help.lnchSoftLim: The RPM point that the launch control ignition timing adjustment will engage (When under launch conditions). Should be below the hard rev limit RPM
help.lnchRetard: When under launch conditions (Eg Clutch engaged) the ignition timing will be set to this when above the Soft rev limit. This will override any other ignition modifiers
help.lnchHardLim: The RPM point above which the fuel and/or ignition will be cut when launch is active (Eg Clutch engaged). See the Engine Protection dialog to set whether it is fuel, ignition or both that are cut.
help.lnchFuelAdd: The additional fuel % that will be added during Soft and Hard launch conditions. Set to 0 for no fuel modifier.

help.ADCFILTER_MAP: This setting is only available when using the Instantaneious MAP sampling method. Recommended value: 20
help.ADCFILTER_BARO: This setting is only available when using an external Baro sensor. Recommended value: 64
help.boostIntv: The closed loop control interval will run every this many ms. Generally values between 50% and 100% of the valve frequency work best
help.VVTasOnOff: Whether or not the VVT table should be treated as on and off control only. If you are using the VVT map to control a switch, this should be Yes. If you are using the VVT control to drive a PWM signal, this should be No
help.stagedInjSizePri: Size of the primary injectors. The sum of the Pri and Sec injectors values MUST match the value used in the req_fuel calculation
help.stagedInjSizeSec: Size of the secondary injectors. The sum of the Pri and Sec injectors values MUST match the value used in the req_fuel calculation
help.resetControl:
How to control the Arduino's automatic reset feature. NOTE: Some of these settings require modifying your hardware and replacing the Arduino bootloader. See the Wiki for more details.

Disabled: Allow the Arduino to reset when a new serial connection is made.

Prevent When Running: Hold the control pin high while the engine is running.

Prevent Always: Always hold the control pin high.

Serial Command: Normally hold the control pin high, but pull it low when the 'U' serial command is issued and reset upon receiving more data.
help.resetControlPin: The Arduino pin used to control resets.
